{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f1ae9c64-972c-47ba-b601-80201c6d1c2a","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:~/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process and collect a trace:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps                          # get the PID\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**3. Copy the trace file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**4. Analyze** by opening `trace.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView** (Windows), or convert to **Speedscope** format for browser-based viewing:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope\n# open the .json at https://www.speedscope.app\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- `--duration 00:00:30` keeps the file small; adjust as needed.\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use a **sidecar** or the `DOTNET_DiagnosticPorts` env var with `dotnet-dsrouter` for out-of-process collection.\n- For production, `--profile cpu-sampling` is low-overhead (~5%).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"750012e5-b13d-4a8f-9728-08fccb472c03","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge question, not a code task, so I'll provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":416},"id":"1d789d66-1b61-4035-b8d7-c346aa396599","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:51:35.105Z","parentId":"fa0b91e8-44c4-47af-b145-59db48aa0fea"}
